The Two Pointer Technique is an algorithmic approach where you use two indices (pointers)
to traverse a data structure (usually an array or string) efficiently.
It often reduces the time complexity from O(n²) to O(n).

1. Opposite Direction Pointers
Used when the array is sorted.

2. Same Direction Pointers (Sliding Window)
Used for subarray/substring problems.

Use it when you see:
✅ Sorted arrays
✅ Pair/triplet sum problems
✅ Subarray/substring questions
✅ Palindrome checking
✅ Removing duplicates
✅ Merging sorted arrays